WEBVTT

1
00:01:08.171 --> 00:01:10.131
You must be
getting quite bored of these.


2
00:01:11.257 --> 00:01:12.759
Never dull
to discuss the work.


3
00:01:12.842 --> 00:01:15.136
Okay, well, I thought we could
just jump straight in,


4
00:01:15.178 --> 00:01:16.471
if that's okay with you.

5
00:01:16.554 --> 00:01:18.598
- By all means.
- Okay.


6
00:01:21.142 --> 00:01:22.644
Hello.

7
00:01:22.727 --> 00:01:25.438
Liam Somers' story
of a fading patriarch


8
00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:27.649
presiding over
a grief-stricken family


9
00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:30.193
has been described
as one of the most striking


10
00:01:30.276 --> 00:01:31.653
debuts of the year.

11
00:01:31.694 --> 00:01:34.948
Here with us to discuss
his first novel is the author.


12
00:01:34.989 --> 00:01:36.491
Thank you
for joining us, Liam.


13
00:01:37.283 --> 00:01:38.743
Thanks for having me.

14
00:01:38.827 --> 00:01:42.205
So, I thought we could start off
by touching on the inspiration


15
00:01:42.288 --> 00:01:43.414
behind the novel.

16
00:01:43.456 --> 00:01:47.585
What exactly is it that drew you
to tell this story?


17
00:02:58.406 --> 00:02:59.866
- Hello?
- Liam.


18
00:02:59.908 --> 00:03:01.242
It's Hattie from the agency.

19
00:03:01.284 --> 00:03:03.161
I'm on my way
to a lesson. Can it wait?


20
00:03:03.203 --> 00:03:06.414
- We cancelled that.
- Something's come in for you.


21
00:03:26.059 --> 00:03:28.561
Writers tend to say
they're a morning person,


22
00:03:28.603 --> 00:03:30.480
or an evening kind of writer.

23
00:03:30.563 --> 00:03:32.273
I don't subscribe to that.

24
00:03:33.483 --> 00:03:35.485
If you're writing,
you're writing.


25
00:03:35.568 --> 00:03:37.195
Simple as that.

26
00:03:43.284 --> 00:03:46.955
It's not something
that can be deferred or denied


27
00:03:47.038 --> 00:03:48.831
if you have to do it.

28
00:03:48.915 --> 00:03:52.210
Which, by the way, is
the prerequisite for writing.


29
00:03:52.293 --> 00:03:54.462
You don't have
a choice in the matter.


30
00:03:55.088 --> 00:03:56.673
You must write.

31
00:04:21.406 --> 00:04:23.157
Listen, if I knew where

32
00:04:23.199 --> 00:04:24.409
the ideas came from,

33
00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:26.327
I'd have written,
and indeed been paid


34
00:04:26.411 --> 00:04:28.079
a hell of a lot
more than I have.


35
00:04:28.162 --> 00:04:30.498
Bearing in mind
that I've been prolific


36
00:04:30.581 --> 00:04:32.250
and not badly off,

37
00:04:32.292 --> 00:04:35.336
the short answer is
I don't know.


38
00:04:44.262 --> 00:04:46.973
I know writers who obsess.

39
00:04:47.056 --> 00:04:49.600
"How do I
say something original?


40
00:04:50.476 --> 00:04:52.770
"Am I saying
something unique?"


41
00:04:53.521 --> 00:04:54.605
I'm sorry.

42
00:04:54.689 --> 00:04:56.274
There are no new ideas.

43
00:04:57.483 --> 00:04:59.444
Most writers
are reconciled to the fact.


44
00:04:59.527 --> 00:05:02.697
And if they're not,
they pretty soon will be.


45
00:05:13.374 --> 00:05:18.171
Now, average writers
attempt originality.


46
00:05:18.254 --> 00:05:20.006
They fail. Universally.

47
00:05:21.090 --> 00:05:24.260
Good writers have the sense
to borrow from their betters.


48
00:05:28.014 --> 00:05:32.352
But the greats,
great writers... steal.


49
00:06:07.762 --> 00:06:10.306
- Good morning.
- Good morning.


50
00:06:10.390 --> 00:06:12.558
- Mr. Somers.
- It's Liam.


51
00:06:16.646 --> 00:06:18.940
If you'd like
to follow me this way, please.


52
00:06:35.832 --> 00:06:37.500
You'll find him just there.

53
00:06:37.542 --> 00:06:39.085
I'll take that, shall I?

54
00:06:39.502 --> 00:06:40.795
Thank you.

55
00:06:46.801 --> 00:06:48.678
Hello. I'm Liam.

56
00:06:51.931 --> 00:06:53.558
You must be Bertie.

57
00:06:53.599 --> 00:06:55.435
You've done your homework.

58
00:06:57.395 --> 00:07:00.273
- Are your parents around?
- They're up at the house.


59
00:07:00.356 --> 00:07:01.983
Why?

60
00:07:02.066 --> 00:07:05.027
I usually speak to parents
before the first lesson.


61
00:07:10.741 --> 00:07:11.659
It's fine.

62
00:07:11.701 --> 00:07:13.244
I can get
my father if you want?


63
00:07:13.286 --> 00:07:15.746
- I'm sure he won't mind.
- No, I don't wanna disturb.


64
00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:17.206
But you want
to meet him, right?


65
00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:18.374
- It's fine.
- He's only writing.


66
00:07:18.416 --> 00:07:19.709
No, it's fine!

67
00:07:23.004 --> 00:07:24.380
Okay.

68
00:07:28.342 --> 00:07:30.470
So, what are we working on?

69
00:07:30.511 --> 00:07:32.638
We are working on tragedy.

70
00:07:33.431 --> 00:07:34.390
Modern? Ancient?

71
00:07:34.474 --> 00:07:36.601
I don't need you
to turn the pages.


72
00:07:43.524 --> 00:07:45.026
Congratulations, by the way.

73
00:07:45.067 --> 00:07:48.529
English Literature is one of
the most competitive courses.


74
00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:51.324
Oxford don't shortlist
many candidates


75
00:07:51.365 --> 00:07:52.325
so your aptitude test

76
00:07:52.408 --> 00:07:54.035
must have been
very impressive.


77
00:07:57.705 --> 00:07:59.081
But that test is one thing.

78
00:07:59.165 --> 00:08:01.250
The interviews,
the college-specific tests,


79
00:08:01.334 --> 00:08:03.211
- they're different.
- You'll need to cultivate


80
00:08:03.252 --> 00:08:04.504
the kind of critical thinking

81
00:08:04.587 --> 00:08:08.424
that might not
be familiar to you... yet.


82
00:08:09.425 --> 00:08:11.177
Kind of a house style.

83
00:08:18.559 --> 00:08:21.020
They staple
at Oxford, don't they?


84
00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:24.565
You can do it
in the house style.


85
00:08:44.835 --> 00:08:46.087
Liam.

86
00:08:46.671 --> 00:08:49.549
- Mrs. Sinclair.
- Helene.


87
00:08:50.758 --> 00:08:53.177
Thanks for coming
on such short notice.


88
00:08:54.387 --> 00:08:55.513
Your CV was impressive.

89
00:08:55.555 --> 00:08:57.682
Your agency speaks
very highly of you.


90
00:08:57.765 --> 00:08:58.808
That's kind of them.

91
00:08:58.891 --> 00:09:01.602
- Well, I should hope not.
- I should hope it's true.


92
00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:04.772
You've a beautiful home,
Mrs. Sinclair.


93
00:09:04.855 --> 00:09:07.567
Thank you. Summer suits it.

94
00:09:08.442 --> 00:09:11.862
- This is the reading room.
- It's usually only me in here.


95
00:09:15.866 --> 00:09:17.660
We don't use
the front entrance much.


96
00:09:17.743 --> 00:09:19.579
There is
a back door to the garden.


97
00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:21.122
This is beautiful.

98
00:09:23.332 --> 00:09:24.625
Thank you.

99
00:09:24.709 --> 00:09:25.876
You made it?

100
00:09:26.335 --> 00:09:28.963
It's kind of... numinous.

101
00:09:31.382 --> 00:09:33.342
And you've met Ellis.

102
00:09:33.384 --> 00:09:35.595
You're laying
the table for four tonight.


103
00:09:35.678 --> 00:09:36.596
Yes, ma'am.

104
00:09:36.679 --> 00:09:39.473
Any dietary
requirements, Mr. Somers?


105
00:09:39.557 --> 00:09:41.851
Actually, I'm vegan.

106
00:09:42.351 --> 00:09:43.644
Wonderful.

107
00:09:44.812 --> 00:09:47.523
And this is
my favorite acquisition.


108
00:09:48.566 --> 00:09:49.692
I bought it from the artist

109
00:09:49.775 --> 00:09:51.652
when she didn't
win the Turner.


110
00:09:51.986 --> 00:09:53.696
Kind of a consolation.

111
00:09:54.447 --> 00:09:56.616
She's a collector's
darling now, of course,


112
00:09:56.657 --> 00:09:58.576
but I found her.

113
00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:03.247
It's adapted from Bernini's
Apollo and Daphne.


114
00:10:03.331 --> 00:10:05.666
- Do you know it?
- I know the story.


115
00:10:05.750 --> 00:10:06.834
Hmm.

116
00:10:06.876 --> 00:10:08.711
Never had
the heart to sell it.


117
00:10:08.961 --> 00:10:10.421
Why would you?

118
00:10:10.463 --> 00:10:12.006
That's my job. I'm a curator.

119
00:10:12.089 --> 00:10:14.008
Shouldn't really
get sentimental.


120
00:10:16.594 --> 00:10:17.845
Something to drink?

121
00:10:17.928 --> 00:10:19.680
You'd like a beer,
wouldn't you?


122
00:11:35.381 --> 00:11:38.426
You know, Liam graduated
with a First in English.


123
00:11:39.844 --> 00:11:41.554
So why is he a tutor?

124
00:11:41.637 --> 00:11:42.722
Well, must be a vocation.

125
00:11:42.763 --> 00:11:45.766
He wants to share
his knowledge, his experience.


126
00:11:46.892 --> 00:11:49.019
We thought it best
Bertie spend the last


127
00:11:49.103 --> 00:11:50.438
of the summer term here

128
00:11:50.479 --> 00:11:52.940
so he can focus
on his entrance exams.


129
00:11:53.607 --> 00:11:54.692
You thought it best?

130
00:11:54.734 --> 00:11:57.319
Well, that school
has let you down enough.


131
00:11:57.361 --> 00:12:00.072
I wasn't going
to leave this up to chance.


132
00:12:00.156 --> 00:12:01.782
You must be good.

133
00:12:05.536 --> 00:12:06.829
Evening, all.

134
00:12:10.583 --> 00:12:12.752
Bonsoir,   my love.

135
00:12:15.588 --> 00:12:17.006
How goes it, Bert?

136
00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:22.511
Liam, isn't it?

137
00:12:22.595 --> 00:12:25.055
- Yes, Mr. Sinclair.
- Oh. Thank you.


138
00:12:25.848 --> 00:12:27.516
You've come on a good day.

139
00:12:27.558 --> 00:12:29.977
Ellis does a mean roast lamb.

140
00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:32.313
Thank you.

141
00:12:36.317 --> 00:12:37.651
Music.

142
00:12:38.736 --> 00:12:40.780
We had Rachmaninoff yesterday.

143
00:12:40.863 --> 00:12:42.573
Well, give me
three good reasons


144
00:12:42.615 --> 00:12:45.326
not to listen
to him today and...


145
00:12:45.910 --> 00:12:47.286
I'll change my mind.

146
00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:49.538
Why don't
we ask our guest?


147
00:12:53.042 --> 00:12:55.336
Liam, what do you
think of Rachmaninoff?


148
00:13:00.174 --> 00:13:01.842
Um...

149
00:13:01.926 --> 00:13:06.055
He was the last great
Russian romantic composer.


150
00:13:06.096 --> 00:13:07.431
And...

151
00:13:07.473 --> 00:13:11.852
known for his piano concertos
more than his symphonies.


152
00:13:11.894 --> 00:13:12.937
His, um...

153
00:13:12.978 --> 00:13:14.855
He was
the conductor of the Bolshoi


154
00:13:14.939 --> 00:13:16.148
when the Russian...

155
00:13:16.232 --> 00:13:17.900
First Russian Revolution
began...


156
00:13:17.942 --> 00:13:19.860
The music. She meant,

157
00:13:19.902 --> 00:13:22.071
"What did you
think of the music?"


158
00:13:26.158 --> 00:13:27.451
I don't, um...

159
00:13:28.994 --> 00:13:30.371
I'm not familiar.

160
00:13:33.165 --> 00:13:34.542
Rachmaninoff it is, then.

161
00:13:36.627 --> 00:13:38.796
Last great Russian romantic.

162
00:13:46.804 --> 00:13:49.849
So, what did
you two study today?


163
00:13:50.307 --> 00:13:52.017
Hamlet,   for the most part.

164
00:13:52.059 --> 00:13:54.728
Oh, you looked into
the manuscript tradition yet?


165
00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:57.982
- I've got, uh, a few articles.
- Hmm.


166
00:13:58.023 --> 00:14:00.234
I can make up a reading list.

167
00:14:00.776 --> 00:14:01.777
Thanks.

168
00:14:01.819 --> 00:14:03.237
You can
thank him when you get in.


169
00:14:03.279 --> 00:14:05.364
If. If you get in.

170
00:14:05.865 --> 00:14:07.283
We should have
a chat about the lesson.


171
00:14:07.324 --> 00:14:08.492
See how it went.

172
00:14:08.576 --> 00:14:09.660
Well, I'm sure
Bertie has some...


173
00:14:09.743 --> 00:14:10.953
I'm sure he does.

174
00:14:10.995 --> 00:14:13.497
Which is why
we'll discuss it after dinner.


175
00:14:13.581 --> 00:14:14.623
You can wait
in the drawing room


176
00:14:14.707 --> 00:14:16.083
when you're finished eating.

177
00:14:16.166 --> 00:14:17.418
Liam...

178
00:14:19.378 --> 00:14:20.921
You're out.

179
00:14:51.619 --> 00:14:53.078
We'd like you to stay.

180
00:14:54.246 --> 00:14:55.915
Is this from the agency?

181
00:14:55.998 --> 00:14:58.626
I think we can part ways
with the agency here.


182
00:14:59.376 --> 00:15:01.253
We prefer a personal bond.

183
00:15:01.295 --> 00:15:04.089
There have been
incidents in the past.


184
00:15:04.131 --> 00:15:05.716
With guests?

185
00:15:05.799 --> 00:15:07.051
With staff.

186
00:15:08.093 --> 00:15:09.970
We told them
we no longer need a tutor.


187
00:15:10.012 --> 00:15:12.139
Didn't wanna
compromise your relationship.


188
00:15:12.181 --> 00:15:14.600
It's so important
Bertie has someone on his side


189
00:15:14.642 --> 00:15:15.893
that knows the English system.

190
00:15:15.976 --> 00:15:17.478
I studied in Paris
and New York.


191
00:15:17.519 --> 00:15:19.438
And his father didn't go,
of course.


192
00:15:22.274 --> 00:15:23.567
Non-disclosure.

193
00:15:24.735 --> 00:15:25.819
He's very protective.

194
00:15:25.903 --> 00:15:27.821
Getting close to the end,
so he tells me.


195
00:15:27.905 --> 00:15:30.240
Yes. Five years
since the last one.


196
00:15:30.324 --> 00:15:32.326
The subject of your thesis.

197
00:15:34.411 --> 00:15:35.663
It's on your CV.

198
00:15:40.918 --> 00:15:44.838
You'll report to me
at the end of every lesson


199
00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:48.175
- about Bertie's progress.
- Come and find me.


200
00:15:48.258 --> 00:15:50.386
He has to get in, Liam.

201
00:15:53.305 --> 00:15:57.059
Uh, he doesn't know
about the thesis, does he,


202
00:15:57.101 --> 00:15:58.686
Mrs. Sinclair?

203
00:15:58.769 --> 00:16:00.187
I'm sure he'd be flattered.

