00:20:50.352 --> 00:20:53.313
All right, you've got
a party trick. I... I get it.


226
00:20:53.355 --> 00:20:54.898
I'm sure it helped
you get your First.


227
00:20:54.982 --> 00:20:56.858
But I can't use it,
and I don't need it.


228
00:20:57.567 --> 00:20:59.695
So, why don't you
fetch me that reading list?


229
00:21:01.071 --> 00:21:03.323
Shall I write it down
so you don't forget?


230
00:22:00.339 --> 00:22:01.506
How did it go?

231
00:22:01.590 --> 00:22:05.093
- Well.
- Independent research, mainly.


232
00:22:06.303 --> 00:22:08.013
Is that your usual practice?

233
00:22:08.722 --> 00:22:09.890
It varies.

234
00:22:09.931 --> 00:22:11.516
For a student
of Bertie's intelligence,


235
00:22:11.558 --> 00:22:13.894
I'd say independence
is a good thing.


236
00:22:16.313 --> 00:22:18.607
You're the best
resource he could have.


237
00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:20.233
He needs to be
making use of you.


238
00:22:20.317 --> 00:22:22.569
Otherwise, why are you here?

239
00:22:23.737 --> 00:22:25.322
I'll make sure he does.

240
00:22:25.781 --> 00:22:26.990
Good.

241
00:22:41.505 --> 00:22:43.298
That's Tchaikovsky, isn't it?

242
00:22:44.591 --> 00:22:46.468
June,   from   The Seasons.

243
00:22:48.136 --> 00:22:50.222
I thought you weren't
familiar with classical.


244
00:22:50.263 --> 00:22:51.681
I'm learning.

245
00:22:51.765 --> 00:22:53.600
Me, too. Trying.

246
00:22:54.684 --> 00:22:56.520
Are you
the only one who plays?


247
00:22:57.604 --> 00:22:59.439
Bertie used to.

248
00:22:59.523 --> 00:23:01.108
Beautifully.

249
00:23:01.650 --> 00:23:03.402
His brother wrote.

250
00:23:03.902 --> 00:23:05.779
Mostly short stories.

251
00:23:06.279 --> 00:23:07.239
Like you.

252
00:23:07.322 --> 00:23:09.324
He took after his father.

253
00:23:13.036 --> 00:23:15.330
He likes
to have someone around.


254
00:23:16.373 --> 00:23:17.416
An amanuensis.

255
00:23:17.499 --> 00:23:19.751
Used to be me
at the start.


256
00:23:21.128 --> 00:23:25.006
- We don't talk about his work.
- We don't talk about Felix.


257
00:23:25.048 --> 00:23:27.509
Follow those rules
and you should be fine.


258
00:23:32.514 --> 00:23:33.807
Of course.

259
00:24:06.882 --> 00:24:09.634
Great writers... steal.

260
00:24:11.761 --> 00:24:14.306
But do you think
it's inevitable


261
00:24:14.389 --> 00:24:17.517
- that elements of your...
- personal life


262
00:24:17.601 --> 00:24:19.436
seep into your work?

263
00:24:19.519 --> 00:24:23.148
Um, you're somebody
who has experienced


264
00:24:23.231 --> 00:24:24.357
great personal tragedy,

265
00:24:24.441 --> 00:24:27.986
and I'm wondering
if the loss of your son


266
00:24:28.028 --> 00:24:31.114
has had a direct impact
on the nature of your writing.


267
00:24:32.782 --> 00:24:34.367
If I were drawing on my life,

268
00:24:34.409 --> 00:24:37.329
I'd be writing memoir,
not fiction.


269
00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:42.501
But if you're asking
if it has affected my writing,


270
00:24:42.542 --> 00:24:43.793
the answer is yes.

271
00:24:43.835 --> 00:24:48.757
In as much as
any loss affects one's life.


272
00:24:50.717 --> 00:24:52.469
Losing a child is...

273
00:24:54.429 --> 00:24:55.597
losing a part of oneself.

274
00:24:55.639 --> 00:24:57.474
And bound up with the grief is

275
00:24:57.516 --> 00:24:59.726
a profound sense
of injustice...


276
00:25:00.894 --> 00:25:02.145
...of being robbed.

277
00:25:02.187 --> 00:25:03.897
And when
they take their own life...


278
00:25:06.816 --> 00:25:08.068
one is...

279
00:25:08.693 --> 00:25:11.071
compelled to the unthinkable.

280
00:25:14.491 --> 00:25:17.035
To grieve the child
is to grieve the killer.


281
00:25:18.578 --> 00:25:19.829
But if you're
asking me seriously,


282
00:25:19.871 --> 00:25:21.748
and I sincerely
hope that you're not,


283
00:25:21.831 --> 00:25:25.126
whether my son's death
has inspired my writing,


284
00:25:25.168 --> 00:25:26.670
the answer is no,
I will not be writing


285
00:25:26.711 --> 00:25:29.297
- about his death.
- I will be writing


286
00:25:29.381 --> 00:25:30.340
in spite of it.

287
00:25:30.382 --> 00:25:31.967
And you will have
your novel...


288
00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:34.678
...when it is ready.

289
00:25:34.719 --> 00:25:37.597
Mr. Sinclair.

290
00:25:39.349 --> 00:25:40.850
Mr. Sinclair.

291
00:26:02.998 --> 00:26:04.457
Liam, just family tonight.

292
00:26:04.499 --> 00:26:06.835
There will be fixings
in the guest house.


293
00:26:06.876 --> 00:26:09.212
- Sure. See you tomorrow.
- Three, four,


294
00:26:09.254 --> 00:26:11.923
- close the door.
- Five, six, pick up sticks.


295
00:26:11.965 --> 00:26:14.134
Bingo. Bon appetit.

296
00:27:17.947 --> 00:27:19.741
Oh, good morning, Mr. Somers.

297
00:27:19.783 --> 00:27:21.242
Something I can help you with?

298
00:27:21.284 --> 00:27:24.371
Yes. We've run out of
coffee in my, uh...


299
00:27:24.454 --> 00:27:26.456
- place.
- Can't have that.


300
00:27:26.498 --> 00:27:28.625
- I'll put a pot on now.
- Thanks.


301
00:27:30.085 --> 00:27:31.419
Just getting us some coffee.

302
00:27:31.503 --> 00:27:33.380
I'm glad you're
making yourself useful.


303
00:27:34.923 --> 00:27:36.675
Fucking hell!

304
00:27:51.439 --> 00:27:53.066
Everything okay, Mr. Sinclair?

305
00:27:56.903 --> 00:28:00.156
- Don't you have a lesson?
- Bertie's just setting up.


306
00:28:17.173 --> 00:28:18.341
The printer.

307
00:28:18.425 --> 00:28:19.843
What
are you trying to do?


308
00:28:19.884 --> 00:28:21.094
Print something.

309
00:28:21.553 --> 00:28:22.929
Do you mind?

310
00:28:30.687 --> 00:28:33.982
- The printer's the problem.
- Nothing to do with that thing.


311
00:28:41.448 --> 00:28:44.451
- My dad worked in IT.
- Oh, sins of the father.


312
00:28:44.868 --> 00:28:46.453
Yeah, I know a bit.

313
00:28:49.664 --> 00:28:51.374
Thanks.

314
00:28:51.416 --> 00:28:53.877
- That's Winterson.
- I beg your pardon?


315
00:28:53.918 --> 00:28:56.755
"Empty space and points
of light." Jeanette Winterson.


316
00:28:56.796 --> 00:28:59.382
Final words
of   Sexing the Cherry.


317
00:29:00.842 --> 00:29:02.343
"And even
the most solid of things


318
00:29:02.385 --> 00:29:03.678
"and the most real,
the best loved


319
00:29:03.720 --> 00:29:06.014
"and the well-known
are only hand-shadows


320
00:29:06.055 --> 00:29:09.225
"on the wall. Empty space
and points of light."


321
00:29:15.023 --> 00:29:16.191
Oh.

322
00:29:16.232 --> 00:29:17.692
Good spot.

323
00:29:20.111 --> 00:29:21.362
Is it research?

324
00:29:21.446 --> 00:29:22.906
Close the door
on your way out, will you?


325
00:29:22.947 --> 00:29:24.532
Mustn't keep Bert waiting.

326
00:29:38.755 --> 00:29:41.424
Hope you
like it strong, Mr. Somers.


327
00:29:42.217 --> 00:29:43.510
Thank you.

328
00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:46.513
It's Liam.

329
00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:48.389
I know.

330
00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:17.585
Might be useful
if I could read


331
00:30:17.669 --> 00:30:19.003
some of what you're writing.

332
00:30:19.087 --> 00:30:20.588
Useful for who?

333
00:30:45.238 --> 00:30:47.115
No, Liam.

334
00:30:47.949 --> 00:30:49.325
Can't touch the buds.

335
00:30:50.743 --> 00:30:51.744
Why not?

336
00:30:51.786 --> 00:30:52.912
It's rhododendron.

337
00:30:52.996 --> 00:30:55.039
Have you never been
in a garden before?


338
00:30:56.291 --> 00:30:58.626
Not everyone
has gardens like this.


339
00:31:00.044 --> 00:31:01.379
It's poisonous.

340
00:31:01.963 --> 00:31:03.464
There's toxins in the sap.

341
00:31:18.730 --> 00:31:20.023
Do you want one?

342
00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:25.612
All right.

343
00:31:26.905 --> 00:31:28.114
Cheers.

344
00:31:36.122 --> 00:31:37.624
It's basically a weed.

345
00:31:39.250 --> 00:31:41.002
Nothing can grow around it.

346
00:31:42.295 --> 00:31:43.963
The roots, they, uh...

347
00:31:44.047 --> 00:31:46.007
They strangle
everything they touch.


348
00:31:46.841 --> 00:31:48.301
It's quite clever, actually.

349
00:31:53.181 --> 00:31:55.058
Felix was obsessed with them.

350
00:31:56.768 --> 00:31:58.102
Rhododendron.

351
00:31:58.811 --> 00:32:00.104
The rose tree.

352
00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:02.106
It's ancient Greek.

353
00:32:19.874 --> 00:32:21.501
They are beautiful.

354
00:32:26.839 --> 00:32:29.008
That's not why
he was obsessed with them.


355
00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:04.544
Oh, no, no, no, no.

356
00:33:12.301 --> 00:33:13.636
Shit!

357
00:33:28.276 --> 00:33:29.610
Oh, Mr. Somers.

358
00:33:29.694 --> 00:33:32.613
There's been a slight
delay to your laundry.


359
00:33:32.697 --> 00:33:35.033
I have brought you
a fresh change of clothes.


360
00:33:35.074 --> 00:33:38.369
I'll just put them down here,

361
00:33:38.453 --> 00:33:39.662
if that's all right?

362
00:33:39.704 --> 00:33:42.081
- Sure. Oh, I can do that.
- No, no, no, no.


363
00:33:42.123 --> 00:33:44.000
It's quite all right,
Mr. Somers.


364
00:33:44.333 --> 00:33:47.128
You are expected at dinner.

365
00:34:20.620 --> 00:34:24.123
- Liam, so sorry.
- We should have warned you.


366
00:34:24.165 --> 00:34:26.334
The power tends
to go down in a storm.


367
00:34:28.544 --> 00:34:30.046
The price of isolation.

368
00:34:37.845 --> 00:34:40.473
"And there was."-

369
00:34:43.893 --> 00:34:45.770
Any objections to Beethoven?

370
00:34:52.401 --> 00:34:54.654
You boys didn't lose anything
in the storm, did you?


371
00:34:55.363 --> 00:34:56.823
I didn't.

372
00:34:56.906 --> 00:34:59.033
We were making
great progress, I think.


373
00:34:59.367 --> 00:35:00.993
Oh, in that case,

374
00:35:01.035 --> 00:35:03.371
I may need
to borrow you this evening.


375
00:35:05.248 --> 00:35:08.793
- Computer is playing up again.
- You don't mind, do you, Liam?


376
00:35:11.212 --> 00:35:14.132
That's fine. I have
tomorrow's lesson planned.


377
00:35:14.215 --> 00:35:15.508
Good.

378
00:35:18.803 --> 00:35:20.138
You know,
Liam's a writer, too.


379
00:35:20.179 --> 00:35:21.681
Mmm. Did you show Bertie

380
00:35:21.764 --> 00:35:23.432
- your student pieces?
- No, no.


381
00:35:24.142 --> 00:35:25.476
I've seen the novel.

382
00:35:26.602 --> 00:35:28.229
Tower 24.

383
00:35:28.604 --> 00:35:30.189
Working title.

384
00:35:30.898 --> 00:35:32.400
It's actually quite good.

385
00:35:33.192 --> 00:35:34.569
Reads like a Sinclair.

386
00:35:35.319 --> 00:35:37.363
That's why the desk lamp
is burning into the night.


387
00:35:37.446 --> 00:35:39.240
I haven't worked
on it in a long time.


388
00:35:39.323 --> 00:35:41.784
It's, um, it's not finished.

389
00:35:41.826 --> 00:35:43.286
Then why does Bertie have it?

390
00:35:56.215 --> 00:35:57.175
Thanks.

391
00:35:57.216 --> 00:35:58.301
Come and see me
after dinner.


392
00:35:58.384 --> 00:35:59.802
You know where I am.

393
00:36:05.516 --> 00:36:06.851
It suits you.

394
00:36:07.393 --> 00:36:09.228
Felix's clothes.

395
00:36:25.953 --> 00:36:27.788
This damn thing
buckles in a storm,


396
00:36:27.872 --> 00:36:30.750
and I need to know
that my work is safe.


397
00:36:30.833 --> 00:36:32.251
You've got
multiple backups, right?


398
00:36:32.335 --> 00:36:33.961
Oh, I used to have
people do that for me.


399
00:36:34.045 --> 00:36:36.297
- PAs, you know.
- But not anymore.


400
00:36:36.339 --> 00:36:38.466
Well, people like
that can be very nosy.


401
00:36:41.219 --> 00:36:42.678
You need
to enter your password.


402
00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:44.222
Okay.

403
00:36:50.353 --> 00:36:52.605
I can run a backup
to the Cloud if you want.


404
00:36:52.688 --> 00:36:53.898
Oh, absolutely not.

405
00:36:53.981 --> 00:36:56.275
I don't give my work away
for free.


406
00:36:57.318 --> 00:36:59.695
Looks like there's
another server running.


407
00:37:00.363 --> 00:37:01.364
Is it here?

408
00:37:01.447 --> 00:37:04.033
- Oh, that...
- Oh, it's next door.


409
00:37:04.116 --> 00:37:06.702
- Used to be part of the study.
- Don't need the space.


410
00:37:06.786 --> 00:37:09.664
- You want me to shut it down?
- No, keep it running.


411
00:37:09.705 --> 00:37:11.165
Just in case.

412
00:37:11.457 --> 00:37:13.125
Okay.

413
00:37:13.209 --> 00:37:16.170
Now, you should be
safe for the next storm.


414
00:37:17.255 --> 00:37:18.297
Goodnight, Mr. Sinclair.

415
00:37:18.339 --> 00:37:20.466
Wow, that was quick.

416
00:37:23.427 --> 00:37:24.637
Scotch?

417
00:37:25.846 --> 00:37:27.306
Sit down.

418
00:37:28.975 --> 00:37:30.810
If you're serious
about doing this,


419
00:37:30.893 --> 00:37:34.188
you must bear
one thought cheerfully in mind


420
00:37:34.230 --> 00:37:36.482
whenever you put pen to paper.

421
00:37:36.524 --> 00:37:42.071
Whenever you read,
eat, drink, fuck, whatever,


422
00:37:42.154 --> 00:37:43.948
one thought. One simple one.

423
00:37:44.448 --> 00:37:46.409
Good writers borrow.

424
00:37:46.450 --> 00:37:49.328
- Great writers steal.
- Don't tell me you're a fan.


425
00:37:53.666 --> 00:37:55.293
There is a new novel.

426
00:37:55.334 --> 00:37:57.295
Started a while back.

427
00:37:58.337 --> 00:37:59.839
Almost over the line.

428
00:38:01.632 --> 00:38:04.468
I was wondering
if you might be on hand


429
00:38:04.510 --> 00:38:05.845
for the final stretch.

430
00:38:05.928 --> 00:38:08.431
Keep the story safe,
provide some amusement.


431
00:38:08.514 --> 00:38:11.183
I've found in the past
that can be really useful.


432
00:38:11.267 --> 00:38:14.103
Someone separate from work.

433
00:38:14.186 --> 00:38:16.314
You know,
not a writer, preferably.


434
00:38:16.355 --> 00:38:17.773
Well, not a real one.

435
00:38:19.775 --> 00:38:21.485
So easy to forget...

436
00:38:21.527 --> 00:38:23.112
it's only really a game.

437
00:38:23.154 --> 00:38:25.656
Oh, don't want to distract
from Bert's studies.


438
00:38:25.698 --> 00:38:27.199
No. No, you wouldn't.

439
00:38:27.283 --> 00:38:29.452
And I'd pay, of course.

440
00:38:30.745 --> 00:38:32.288
Take it you're in?

441
00:38:35.458 --> 00:38:37.418
We'll make a thief of you yet.

442
00:38:42.840 --> 00:38:44.425
What's it called?

443
00:38:45.843 --> 00:38:47.303
Rose Tree.

444
00:38:48.387 --> 00:38:49.847
What do you think?

445
00:38:52.808 --> 00:38:54.310
I love it.

446
00:39:02.026 --> 00:39:03.736
What did
you two talk about?


447
00:39:05.821 --> 00:39:08.407
Liam, I won't tell.

448
00:39:13.746 --> 00:39:15.664
Oh, hello. Are you lost?

449
00:39:16.165 --> 00:39:17.833
Ah! The missing mother.

450
00:39:19.710 --> 00:39:21.379
What are we discussing?

451
00:39:22.380 --> 00:39:23.589
Bertie.

452
00:39:23.839 --> 00:39:25.424
How he's doing.

453
00:39:26.384 --> 00:39:28.427
- Course.
- The boy wonder.


454
00:39:29.095 --> 00:39:31.764
Going to be another
late one I'm afraid, my love.


455
00:39:32.473 --> 00:39:33.682
Pay me a visit, won't you?

456
00:39:33.766 --> 00:39:35.434
Of course, darling.

457
00:40:28.237 --> 00:40:30.197
Friends, family,

458
