461
00:40:37.913 --> 00:40:39.665
you are alone.

462
00:40:39.748 --> 00:40:41.125
Armed only with your craft

463
00:40:41.208 --> 00:40:44.670
and, hopefully,
your talent.


464
00:40:47.756 --> 00:40:48.757
What's that?

465
00:40:48.841 --> 00:40:50.676
It's an essay of yours.

466
00:40:52.553 --> 00:40:54.180
This is good, Bertie.

467
00:40:55.264 --> 00:40:57.016
I'd love to have
thought of this.


468
00:41:00.811 --> 00:41:02.521
Your reading list helped.

469
00:41:06.817 --> 00:41:08.110
How can I make it better?

470
00:41:15.159 --> 00:41:16.744
And in your conclusion,
you might wanna to consider


471
00:41:16.827 --> 00:41:19.788
Shakespeare's familiarity
with   Hippolytus.


472
00:41:19.872 --> 00:41:21.290
I didn't know
that you were allowed


473
00:41:21.332 --> 00:41:23.083
to make connections like that,

474
00:41:23.167 --> 00:41:25.503
you know, between texts,
across the genres.


475
00:41:25.544 --> 00:41:27.338
It's like
a whole different thing.


476
00:41:28.464 --> 00:41:31.133
Sorry, but there are
no new ideas.


477
00:41:31.217 --> 00:41:33.594
To our Alexander
and our Aristotle.


478
00:41:33.677 --> 00:41:35.471
Most writers
are reconciled to the fact.


479
00:41:35.513 --> 00:41:37.932
And if they're not,
they very soon will be.


480
00:42:40.452 --> 00:42:41.537
Oh, Liam.

481
00:42:41.579 --> 00:42:42.913
Give that
the once-over, will you?


482
00:42:42.955 --> 00:42:43.872
Yeah.

483
00:42:43.956 --> 00:42:45.624
Flower-Gathering
is my favorite.


484
00:42:45.708 --> 00:42:47.251
From   A Boy's Will.

485
00:42:48.085 --> 00:42:49.628
Oh.

486
00:42:51.672 --> 00:42:53.757
"Are you dumb
because you know me not,


487
00:42:53.841 --> 00:42:56.302
"Or dumb because you know?"

488
00:42:56.802 --> 00:42:58.637
Well spotted. Come in.

489
00:43:00.973 --> 00:43:02.474
Everything's fine.

490
00:43:02.558 --> 00:43:04.810
You've still got
that server running next door.


491
00:43:04.893 --> 00:43:07.187
- Oh, forget that.
- It's dormant.


492
00:43:07.229 --> 00:43:09.732
- Or I can just shut it down.
- Leave it.


493
00:43:10.816 --> 00:43:13.235
Your father
teach you all that?


494
00:43:13.902 --> 00:43:16.363
I learned. He didn't teach me.

495
00:43:16.405 --> 00:43:19.283
I'll wager he's glad
you didn't go into IT.


496
00:43:24.872 --> 00:43:27.082
What are people
saying about me?


497
00:43:33.922 --> 00:43:35.841
People think you've retired.

498
00:43:44.141 --> 00:43:45.726
You are amusing.

499
00:43:55.736 --> 00:43:57.363
Have you only just got out?

500
00:43:59.657 --> 00:44:02.326
We're getting
our money's worth, aren't we?


501
00:44:04.953 --> 00:44:07.414
You and Bertie seem
to be getting along.


502
00:44:08.082 --> 00:44:09.416
This new arrangement isn't

503
00:44:09.500 --> 00:44:11.502
drawing your focus
away from him, is it?


504
00:44:11.543 --> 00:44:13.128
No, not at all.

505
00:44:15.839 --> 00:44:17.633
"What makes an ending?"

506
00:44:18.425 --> 00:44:20.302
That's what
we've been talking about.


507
00:44:21.387 --> 00:44:23.055
He's thinking of his own.

508
00:44:23.639 --> 00:44:24.848
Have you seen it?

509
00:44:24.932 --> 00:44:26.141
No.

510
00:44:26.642 --> 00:44:28.018
But he's writing?

511
00:44:28.102 --> 00:44:29.353
I think so.

512
00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:31.730
I think he's close.

513
00:44:35.901 --> 00:44:37.653
He calls me
"the missing mother,"


514
00:44:37.736 --> 00:44:39.905
because I wasn't
there when our son died.


515
00:44:41.990 --> 00:44:44.410
I was in Venice. The Biennale.

516
00:44:46.662 --> 00:44:47.996
I don't go anymore.

517
00:45:06.974 --> 00:45:09.184
- You're up late.
- So are you.


518
00:45:09.727 --> 00:45:11.937
You know
you're not the first, right?


519
00:45:17.609 --> 00:45:19.111
Get some sleep, Bertie.

520
00:45:23.615 --> 00:45:24.742
Goodnight.

521
00:45:24.783 --> 00:45:26.034
Night.

522
00:45:35.919 --> 00:45:37.421
Say I die.

523
00:45:37.463 --> 00:45:39.173
Right here, right now.

524
00:45:39.214 --> 00:45:41.300
Who owns my words?

525
00:45:41.925 --> 00:45:43.051
I don't mean in a legal sense.

526
00:45:43.093 --> 00:45:45.387
I mean,
testament to experience.


527
00:45:45.471 --> 00:45:47.556
Words I chose
because I believed


528
00:45:47.598 --> 00:45:49.975
they bore witness
to a truth beyond fiction.


529
00:45:50.017 --> 00:45:51.518
Because, when strung together,

530
00:45:51.602 --> 00:45:53.979
they accorded to a music
only I could hear.


531
00:45:54.021 --> 00:45:57.191
Resolved some conflict
raging within me.


532
00:45:58.567 --> 00:46:00.319
Who owns them?

533
00:46:00.402 --> 00:46:05.032
They belong to whoever
chooses to read them.


534
00:46:05.908 --> 00:46:08.285
And since we are
the words we write...


535
00:46:09.286 --> 00:46:10.370
so do we.

536
00:46:10.454 --> 00:46:12.956
Finders fucking keepers.-

537
00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:19.922
Oh. Only gods come out
of the machine, Liam.


538
00:46:21.131 --> 00:46:23.091
Ghosts stay in them.

539
00:46:26.178 --> 00:46:27.930
You've said that before.

540
00:46:28.764 --> 00:46:30.098
In   Pearlescence.

541
00:46:30.140 --> 00:46:31.016
Did I?

542
00:46:31.058 --> 00:46:33.435
Jesus,
I'm repeating myself now.


543
00:46:33.477 --> 00:46:35.437
And from one
of your lesser works.


544
00:46:40.651 --> 00:46:42.945
You know,
I don't even remember


545
00:46:43.028 --> 00:46:44.071
half of that one.

546
00:46:49.952 --> 00:46:51.119
First draft.

547
00:46:51.578 --> 00:46:53.914
Tad shorter than usual.

548
00:46:53.956 --> 00:46:56.250
Thought you might
like to proofread it.


549
00:46:56.291 --> 00:46:57.876
Would that be a problem?

550
00:47:00.712 --> 00:47:02.339
Not if you read mine.

551
00:47:04.299 --> 00:47:06.093
All right.

552
00:47:06.176 --> 00:47:08.428
Drop it in
first thing tomorrow morning.


553
00:48:01.648 --> 00:48:04.026
Dante. Tolstoy. Flaubert.

554
00:48:04.067 --> 00:48:06.069
Not a single one of them read.

555
00:48:06.111 --> 00:48:08.739
What the fuck do they even
teach you at that school?


556
00:48:08.780 --> 00:48:09.865
May as well burn them.

557
00:48:09.948 --> 00:48:12.242
- You may as well be illiterate.
- Are you?


558
00:48:13.201 --> 00:48:15.495
What your brother
would have given to read


559
00:48:15.579 --> 00:48:17.956
any of these works
that you shun.


560
00:48:18.040 --> 00:48:21.001
At least he had
the intellect to read mine.


561
00:48:22.878 --> 00:48:24.880
Oh, Bert, come here.

562
00:48:30.135 --> 00:48:32.346
It's me. It's me.

563
00:48:52.032 --> 00:48:53.992
- Morning.
- Morning.


564
00:48:55.869 --> 00:48:56.954
My novel.

565
00:48:57.245 --> 00:49:00.082
Tower 24.   Longhand.

566
00:49:00.999 --> 00:49:03.460
- Like the best.
- Look forward to it.


567
00:49:04.711 --> 00:49:06.505
Oh, take those, would you?

568
00:49:19.184 --> 00:49:20.852
- I can't do this. He's right.
- Bertie.


569
00:49:20.936 --> 00:49:22.104
I haven't read...

570
00:49:22.145 --> 00:49:23.730
- I don't fucking...
- I don't know enough.


571
00:49:23.772 --> 00:49:24.940
- I've not read enough.
- I'm wasting my time.


572
00:49:24.982 --> 00:49:25.941
I'm wasting your time.

573
00:49:25.983 --> 00:49:27.025
It's just all a fucking waste.

574
00:49:27.109 --> 00:49:28.193
Stop it, stop it. Hey. Hey.

575
00:49:28.276 --> 00:49:29.569
Stop it. Stop it.-

576
00:49:29.611 --> 00:49:30.696
Hey. Listen to me. Look at me.

577
00:49:30.737 --> 00:49:32.030
Take a breath. Take a breath.

578
00:49:32.114 --> 00:49:36.201
- Bertie. Bertie. Look at me.
- Just one breath. One breath.


579
00:49:38.161 --> 00:49:40.205
It's all right. It's okay.

580
00:49:40.872 --> 00:49:42.082
It's okay.

581
00:49:42.332 --> 00:49:43.709
It's okay.

582
00:49:58.223 --> 00:49:59.516
Hey.

583
00:50:05.480 --> 00:50:07.024
I won't let him bother you.

584
00:50:07.107 --> 00:50:08.608
It's too late for that.

585
00:50:09.818 --> 00:50:12.738
You... can go
if you want. I understand.


586
00:50:15.782 --> 00:50:17.743
When you said
I wasn't the first,


587
00:50:18.326 --> 00:50:19.745
what did you mean?

588
00:50:20.954 --> 00:50:22.164
I know I'm not
the first tutor.


589
00:50:22.247 --> 00:50:24.124
But that's not
what you meant, is it?


590
00:50:27.210 --> 00:50:29.713
My father likes
keeping his favorites close.


591
00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:35.093
He moved Felix into the room
next to his, for fuck's sake.


592
00:50:37.345 --> 00:50:38.722
I'm not Felix.

593
00:50:40.974 --> 00:50:42.225
I know.

594
00:50:52.819 --> 00:50:54.529
Take the day off, Bertie.

595
00:50:56.448 --> 00:50:58.200
So you're not leaving?

596
00:50:59.618 --> 00:51:00.786
No.

597
00:51:01.328 --> 00:51:03.121
I'm not going anywhere.

598
00:52:59.321 --> 00:53:00.572
Good swim?

599
00:53:01.406 --> 00:53:02.657
Yeah.

600
00:53:02.699 --> 00:53:04.868
Not as warm as it looks.

601
00:53:06.995 --> 00:53:08.330
Don't do it again.

602
00:53:09.247 --> 00:53:11.082
- I'm sorry?
- Lake's off limits.


603
00:53:11.166 --> 00:53:12.209
For their sake.

604
00:53:12.292 --> 00:53:16.171
It's only been
two years since Felix.


605
00:53:16.213 --> 00:53:17.589
They're a little delicate.

606
00:53:19.132 --> 00:53:21.927
- I'm sorry. I didn't know.
- You do now.


607
00:53:23.094 --> 00:53:25.972
I finished your novel,
by the way.


608
00:53:26.056 --> 00:53:28.225
Bring mine over tonight,
we'll debrief.


609
00:53:28.308 --> 00:53:30.060
I might need
a little more time


610
00:53:30.101 --> 00:53:31.353
to finish reading it.

611
00:53:31.436 --> 00:53:32.938
You found time to swim.

612
00:54:23.613 --> 00:54:24.948
Come in.

613
00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:34.874
I've annotated the text
where I've spotted anything.


614
00:54:34.958 --> 00:54:37.669
There's a cross-referenced
document on my laptop.


615
00:54:38.628 --> 00:54:39.921
Very thorough.

616
00:54:41.214 --> 00:54:43.591
Well, don't keep me
in suspense.


617
00:54:44.301 --> 00:54:46.511
It's like nothing
you've written before.


618
00:54:46.594 --> 00:54:48.013
It was hard to read.

619
00:54:48.513 --> 00:54:49.556
What...

620
00:54:49.639 --> 00:54:51.182
Why?

621
00:54:51.224 --> 00:54:53.601
Because even if
I started writing it,


622
00:54:53.685 --> 00:54:55.312
even if I...

623
00:54:55.395 --> 00:54:57.564
devoted my entire life...

624
00:54:58.106 --> 00:54:59.232
I wouldn't come close.

625
00:54:59.274 --> 00:55:01.609
I mean, the voice,
the rhythm, the cadences.


626
00:55:01.651 --> 00:55:03.945
It just feels... It feels new.

627
00:55:04.029 --> 00:55:05.322
I don't know
how you've done it,


628
00:55:05.363 --> 00:55:07.866
but you sound new.

629
00:55:08.533 --> 00:55:10.744
It very well
could be a masterpiece.


630
00:55:12.037 --> 00:55:13.705
But, um, the ending.

631
00:55:13.788 --> 00:55:15.874
- Part three?
- Mmm-hmm.


632
00:55:16.374 --> 00:55:18.668
It feels
like a different novel.


633
00:55:21.129 --> 00:55:23.381
Like it doesn't belong here.

634
00:55:25.175 --> 00:55:26.259
The work just deserves better.

635
00:55:26.343 --> 00:55:28.595
- I had to tell you that.
- Mmm.


636
00:55:38.229 --> 00:55:40.857
You seem
to have misunderstood, Liam.


637
00:55:42.275 --> 00:55:43.610
We're not peers.

638
00:55:43.651 --> 00:55:45.028
You're a proofreader.

639
00:55:45.070 --> 00:55:47.322
But as you've begun...

640
00:55:48.156 --> 00:55:50.533
we'll suspend
disbelief a while.


641
00:55:52.494 --> 00:55:55.163
Your first novel.

642
00:55:55.246 --> 00:55:57.624
Something of a misnomer,
is it not?


643
00:55:57.665 --> 00:55:59.793
- How do you mean?
- It's not a novel.


644
00:55:59.834 --> 00:56:01.336
It's passable airport fiction.

645
00:56:01.378 --> 00:56:02.712
I can see
why you gave up on it.


646
00:56:04.005 --> 00:56:05.673
Could be tweaked
into a short story,


647
00:56:05.715 --> 00:56:07.550
a novella at best.

648
00:56:07.592 --> 00:56:10.178
I could easily
pass it on to my editor


649
00:56:10.220 --> 00:56:11.388
for a second opinion.

650
00:56:11.429 --> 00:56:13.598
But I have a reputation.

651
00:56:14.599 --> 00:56:16.184
Imagine.

652
00:56:16.226 --> 00:56:18.395
My publisher
wakes up one morning,


653
00:56:18.478 --> 00:56:20.271
finds a message from me

654
00:56:20.313 --> 00:56:22.399
claiming to have found
the next best thing.


655
00:56:22.482 --> 00:56:25.026
- Tower 24.
- He'd think I'd cracked.


656
00:56:26.027 --> 00:56:28.905
I can't put my name
to just anything.


657
00:56:32.325 --> 00:56:33.576
That's years of work.

658
00:56:33.618 --> 00:56:35.578
Really? How frustrating.

659
00:56:35.620 --> 00:56:37.705
Then again,
I'll never get back the hours


660
00:56:37.747 --> 00:56:40.166
I spent reading it.-

661
00:56:40.250 --> 00:56:42.502
We needn't waste
any more time.


662
00:56:45.755 --> 00:56:47.507
- I'm sorry.
- Oh, don't be.


663
00:56:47.590 --> 00:56:49.217
You weren't to know.

664
00:56:49.300 --> 00:56:51.803
Oh, have you
considered teaching?


665
00:56:52.303 --> 00:56:54.222
This isn't about the writing.

666
00:56:54.305 --> 00:56:56.724
Oh, it's only ever
about the writing, Liam.


667
00:56:58.643 --> 00:57:00.645
And I regret to say...

668
00:57:01.938 --> 00:57:03.398
you cannot write.

669
00:57:04.315 --> 00:57:06.151
Send me that document,
would you?


670
00:57:07.485 --> 00:57:08.528
I'll do it before I leave.

671
00:57:08.611 --> 00:57:10.113
- Ah!
- You're not finished yet.


672
00:57:10.155 --> 00:57:11.281
You can find someone else.

673
00:57:11.364 --> 00:57:12.323
Liam.

674
00:57:12.407 --> 00:57:13.992
You signed the agreement.

675
00:57:15.201 --> 00:57:18.538
Great shame
to break your bond now.


676
00:57:18.580 --> 00:57:21.624
I so loathe
dealing with lawyers.


677
00:57:24.794 --> 00:57:26.588
I'm saving your life, Liam.

678
00:57:45.273 --> 00:57:47.567
Fuck!

679
00:58:54.717 --> 00:58:57.804
I thought you didn't
want to do public appearances.


680
00:58:59.180 --> 00:59:00.682
Just dropping
into the conference,


681
00:59:00.723 --> 00:59:01.724
surprise them all.

682
00:59:01.766 --> 00:59:02.809
Spontaneity, darling.

683
00:59:02.850 --> 00:59:04.936
You remember that, don't you?

684
00:59:06.771 --> 00:59:08.773
Ah! The tutor.

